<DOC><DOCNO> AP890720-0070 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 0852EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-China-Typhoon 1stLd-Writethru a0450 07-20 0292</FIRST><SECOND>PM-China-Typhoon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0450,0298</SECOND><HEAD>Storm Batters China, Kills 17</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: Subs 1 graf for 8th, ``The typhoon...'' to UPDATE casualty figuresfrom Philippines. Pickup 9th, ``Gordon's raging...''</HEAD><DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Typhoon Gordon left at least 17 people dead andmore than 100 injured when it slammed into southern China, cuttingcommunication lines and washing away roads and crops, the officialChina Daily reported today.   The paper said 13 people were missing and that damages totaledabout $27 million. The storm hit on Wednesday.   Eight of the dead and 80 of the injured were in Yangjiang, one ofthe hardest hit areas in coastal Guangdong province, the paper said.   About 250 fishing boats capsized, 22 bridges collapsed and 156miles of highway were washed away, the report said.   Eight other people died in Zhaoqing in central Guangdong, and oneperson was killed in the Zhuhai Special Economic Zone, near Macao,where most of the coastal dikes were destroyed and 4,200 acres ofsugar cane fields, rice paddies and fish ponds were flooded, thepaper said.   Thousands of people in the provincial capital of Canton werestranded and telecommunications were knocked out, it said.   The nationally televised evening news on Wednesday showed footageof waves crashing over sea walls, flooded streets and buildings withonly rooftops visible.   The typhoon first hit the Philippines early Sunday with winds ofup to 116 mph, killing 32 people, injuring 43 and leaving almost186,000 people homeless on the islands. It caused at least $30million in damage, according to the Office of Civil Defense.   Gordon's raging winds hit Hong Kong on Tuesday, killing oneperson before moving on to Guangdong province.   It was downgraded to a tropical storm Wednesday morning, theState Meteorological Bureau said.</TEXT></DOC>